    <div class="">
      <h3>Offerings</h3>
      <p>Over time, I refined Mocktail's offerings, based on my team's strengths and the general types of projects we were landing, into three distinct "productized services." Each followed a documented, improvable process ensuring quality and timely delivery. It also made it possible to quickly contract new designers as projects scaled.</p>
      <h5>Offering #1</h5>
      <h4>Sketch</h4>
      <p>The $99 offering that gets us in the door. More than half of all Sketch clients come back for 3+ projects based on their positive experience with the initial engagement.</p>
      <p>One thing Techstars impressed upon me above everything else was their motto of "give first." Mocktail gave first, and got more in return.</p>
      <p>We usually lost $150 on these projects. If you count that as part of our CAC, LTV-as-% goes down to around 435%. It's good for taxes.</p>
      <h5>Offering #2</h5>
      <h4>Cover Art</h4>
      <p>The bread and butter. Subsidized by labels and promo channels, art is cheap to produce (usually a designer's afternoon + some revision cleanup).</p>
      <p>Musicians and labels need a lot of art. Repeating clients had art needs every ~4 months.</p>
      <h5>Offering #3</h5>
      <h4>Visual ID</h4>
      <p>The larger engagement and the core of Mocktail's profit. Lots of logo work and art direction, tied in with some digital strategy.</p><p> Project management time is drastically reduced because almost all of these clients have worked with Mocktail before and know the drill.</p>
    </div>
