      <h2>Lessons Learned</h2>
      <h3>Co-Founders</h3>
      <p>Co-founding really is a little bit like marrying someone. I ultimately ended up buying out my co-founder and growing the team beyond him due to frictions in working style and unrelated personal events. Today I am much, much more intense about vetting the people I collaborate with.</p>
      <h3>Project Management</h3>
      <p>I ran most of the projects that came through Mocktail and learned a huge amount about keeping stakeholders happy, managing communication styles, timelines and deadlines, and putting out fires.</p>
      <h3>Hiring &amp; Firing</h3>
      <p>Just really hard. This is still my weakest (known) area as a designer. I escaped with only a few burned bridges and a deep respect for the importance and craft of hiring good team members.</p>
      <h3>Design</h3>
      <p>During my time with Mocktail I produced upwards of 3,000 logo sketches and almost a hundred art drafts. In-the-trenches practice was a great way to discover and refine my process for logo, iconography, and graphic design.</p>
